Momm- sen's preface contains an account of the manuscripts of the Life, of the chronology of the time, so far as it casts direct light upon the careers of Severinus and Eugippius, and of the references to Eugippius and Severinus in later ecclesiastical writers.1 One who desires a more general view of the period may obtain it by reading the pertinent Chapters of Hodgkin, Dahn‚ or Gibbon, or Julius von Pflugk-Harttung's The Great M igrations, which, translated from the Allgemeine Weltgeschichte, forms the sixth volume in Wright’s H istory of All N ations. Passages referring specifically to Severinus may be found in Pflugk-Harttung’s vol- ume, in the English translation, on pages 2 50 f„ 269, and 296. Julius Jung, in his Ro‘mer und Romamn in den Donauliindern (Innsbruck, 1877),2 pages 133-141‚ Iso-156, etc.‚ discusses the Life with particular reference to the light which it sheds upon the ethnog- raphy and local history of Noricum and the adjacent provinces.
